All 6 tests pass (my 3 + the co-run pickomit), and the repro file is cleaned up. The fix is verified.

## Summary

**Root cause:** In `packages/zod/src/v4/core/util.ts`, `merge(a, b)` unconditionally set `checks: []` in the merged def, silently discarding `.refine()` (and any other check) from *both* operands. When v4.3.0 added guards to `.pick()`/`.omit()`/`.partial()` to throw on refined object schemas, `.merge()` was missed.

**Fix** (`util.ts`, `merge`): before building the merged def, check whether either operand carries checks and throw the same consistent error:

```ts
export function merge(a: schemas.$ZodObject, b: schemas.$ZodObject): any {
  const aChecks = a._zod.def.checks;
  const bChecks = b._zod.def.checks;
  const hasChecks = (aChecks && aChecks.length > 0) || (bChecks && bChecks.length > 0);
  if (hasChecks) {
    throw new Error(".merge() cannot be used on object schemas containing refinements");
  }
  ...
```

This mirrors the existing `pick`/`omit`/`partial` pattern exactly, and — unlike those single-operand methods — checks *both* `a` and `b`, since a refinement on either side would otherwise be lost.

**Verification:**
- `object.test.ts` (51) + `pickomit.test.ts` (16) pass unchanged — no existing v4 merge test relied on the silent drop.
- A temporary repro (removed after running) confirmed: throws when operand A is refined, throws when operand B is refined, and unrefined merges still work normally.

**What could make this wrong (attack):** The report frames throwing as one option ("should it throw?"); a maintainer might instead prefer *preserving* refinements. But throwing is the behavior the issue explicitly requests and the one that's consistent with the `.pick()`/`.omit()`/`.partial()` pass — silent data loss is the worst of the three outcomes, so throwing is the defensible fix. I left the now-redundant `checks: []` line in place (harmless, since both operands are guaranteed check-free past the guard) to keep the diff minimal.
